<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Albert Kennedy Trust</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> Albert Kennedy Trust</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Albert Kennedy Trust (AKT) is a </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">charity that has been working with lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender (LGBT) young people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aged </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">25 and under</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are homeless or in crisis at home</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> since 1989. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ith offices in London, Manchester and, from this year, Newcastle, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e provide a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">range</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of services, including advice and assessment, advocacy, me</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntoring, residential services, peer support and training. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A ye</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ar away from our 25th anniversary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as a charity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and with many of the larger legislative issues for LGBT people now addressed by this and previous governments, we are nevertheless still seeing the same issues arise for young LGBT people as they struggle to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sustain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their lives in their family homes. We maintain that withdrawing the support that currently enables young people to live away from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unsafe or unsuitable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> family homes will disproportionately affect young LGBT people in a negative way. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submissio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n has been drafted at short notice, but AKT staff and trustees are very willing to enter into more detailed discussion with the Select Committee on this and other relevant points.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Please contact Tim </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sigsworth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Chief Executive: </span><a href="mailto:tim@akt.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">tim@akt.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The rise in demand for homelessness services</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over the past two years, the homelessness sector has seen a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rise in demand for services. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Rough Sleeper Statistics repor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ts for 2011 and 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">showed an aggregate 30</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">% rise in street homelessness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and statutory acceptances have risen by 24% over the same period (https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-communities-and-local-government/series/homelessness-statistics)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">By compari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">son</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, over the last 3 years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, AKT has seen a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">97% rise in new contacts in Londo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n, and a 78% rise in Manchester.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="429" height="265" alt="" /><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Capacity</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Meanwhile, the capacity of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">homelessness </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sector is shrinking. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Homeless Link reported that 2012 saw reductions in funding for 58% of projects, with frontline staff reductions in 28%. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">24 night cover services, 22 floating support services, 18 outreach services, 15 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">accommodation services, and 3 day centres closed last y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ear. Services reported reduced outcomes for clients in terms of employment (44%) and accommodation (38%). The same period saw LGBT-specific services shrink from 11% to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">just </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3% of the sector (</span><a href="http://homeless.org.uk/sites/default/files/SNAP2012%20fullreport.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://homeless.org.uk/sites/default/files/SNAP2012%20fullreport.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">LGBT specificities in the homeless picture</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Prevalence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Anecdotal evidence from homelessness services has long maintained that there is a large LGBT youth homeless </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">population; t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">social research suggesting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a sizeable disproportion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of LGBT people in the youth homelessness population</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, particularly in urban areas with LGBT cultural hubs. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Dunne et al (2002) found an estimate of 26% LG</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BT people among the y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">outh </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">homelessness population from homeless agencies in London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (this compares to an estimated 9% prevalence of LGBT people among the general population).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Browne and Davis (2008) found a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">22% </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prevalence of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">homelessness among a sizeable sample of LGBT people l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iving and working in Brighton (this compares to around 8% prevalence of homelessness within the general population).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> By contrast, in the US, where state support for homeless people is far lower, the estimated prevalence of LGBT people in t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he young homeless population is between 25% and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">40% (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Kruks, 1991; Noel and Ochs, 2001; Cochran et al, 2002).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Presenting issues</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Homelessness</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2012-13, 63% of young people in London and 30% of those in Manchester gave homelessness as their primary reason </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for contacting us. The majority of those who contact AKT, particularly in London, are already homeless or living in an unsustainable situation which will result in imminent homelessness.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Family rejection</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The great majority of young people who contact AKT have faced rejection from their families. Many have been asked to leave their homes on coming out (or being outed, an increasing phenomenon in the age of social media). Some have faced violence and abuse, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">some face psychological or religious reparative 'therapies' or rituals, forced marriage or corrective rape (see s4.2.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and s4.2.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, below). Though AKT seeks to reconnect young people with their families wherever it is safe and appropriate to do so, this rem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ains a minority of cases. Many young people, once settled and independent after a period of homelessness, do reconnect with their families at some level, but those who are forced to move back home for lack of options elsewhere</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> often face the same issues an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">again become homeless because of them.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Domestic violence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While only 6% of young people gave domestic violence as their primary reason for contacting AKT last year, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of those who were already or imminently homeless had experienced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> domestic violence. The majority were experiencing violence from family members </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rather than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from partners, which makes accessing services particularly difficult: though definitions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of domestic violence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in homelessness law include familial violence on young</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> people, in practice the vast majority of domestic violence services are aimed at women experiencing partner violence; they are not designed for young people of all genders fleeing violence from their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">families</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Domestic violence includes physical, emotiona</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l, sexual, psychological, financial and verbal abuse. It is AKT's position that frequently and stridently expressed homophobic, biphobic and transphobic language and attitudes are forms of emotional abuse when experienced by LGBT young people in their fami</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly context. Many of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those who contact us have experienced several kinds of abuse from their families over a sustained period of time. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Forced marriage, religious abuse and 'honour'-based violence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">AKT sees a small but steadily growing number of cases where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> young LGBT people have faced increased risks to their safety and wellbeing because of religious and cultural belief. We see a variety of backgrounds in this work, which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in mainstream provision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tends to be aimed at British Muslim women. We have seen cases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of young people from Pentecostal, Jehovah's Witness, Salvation Army and Irish Traveller backgrounds as well as those from Muslim backgrounds. Of these young people the largest </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proportion have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Pentecostal Christian backgrounds. AKT works with these young pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ople to help them find safe and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">positive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> homes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">supportive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> new networks, and legal protection. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sexual exploitation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Around 65% of young gay and bisexual men and around 35% of young trans women working with AKT have exchanged sex for a place to stay. Sexua</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l exploitation of LGBT young homeless people is common: the lack of relevant sex education, the power imbalance between older and younger people, and the club culture prevalent in LGBT commercial hubs all contribute to a situation in which too often, LGBT </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">young homeless people are not offered an opportunity to meaningfully consent to safe sex. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Mental health</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Of the 22% of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">our clients</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> who count themselves as disabled, the most commonly reported form of disability is mental </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">illness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Many of those who do not see themselves as disabled are also in varying levels of mental health distress. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A considerable amount of research has shown that LGBT people, and particularly LGBT youth, are more vulnerable to mental health difficulties than he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">terosexual comparison groups. In particular studies have shown that there are higher rates of attempted suicide and depressive illness in the LGB population (Bagley and Tremblay, 1997, Garofalo et al., 1998, Bagley and D'Augelli, 2000, Webb and Wright, 200</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1, King et al., 2003a). One study of LGB youth report that 39% have attempted suicide compared to 6-10% of the general youth population (Rotherum-Borus et al., 1994); another recent study in Northern Ireland found that 27.1% of young gay or bisexual men ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d attempted suicide (McNamee, 2006). One study of LGBT youth (some of whom had been homeless) found that 64% of transgender youth had attempted suicide (Carolan and Redmond, 2003)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Debt, sanctions and rent arrears</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The majority of young people accessing AK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T's services are claiming benefits for at least some of the time they work with us and over the last year, as the value of benefits has fallen below inflation, we have seen young people resort increasingly to expensive forms of credit.  Many have debts fro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m mobile phone contracts; some have payday loans. Without the means to address these issues robustly they will often fall into rent arrears and risk losing their accommodation and making future tenancies far harder to find. At the same time we have begun t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o notice a pattern of benefit sanctions being applied to young homeless people who may be unable to meet the demands of their jobseeking agreements, or attend courses or placements while homeless. Young homeless people on sanctions also soon fall into rent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> arrears, as they are unable to pay the rent contributions which homeless hostels require; we have even seen some cases of young people being evicted from homeless hostels for this reason.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">LGBT migrants</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over the last year, the number of LGBT migrants app</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roaching AKT for support has increased significantly, particularly in London. Though relatively few have made asy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lum claims, and most are in the UK on student or working visas, they tend to be strongly motivated to stay by experiences of violence, oppressi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on and discrimination in their home countries. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thorough</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> analysis of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">housing and homelessness </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">issues facing LGBT asylum seekers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can be found here: http://www.metropolitan.org.uk/images/Over-Not-Out.pdf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">AKT would suggest that given the likely disproportion of LGBT people in the young homeless population, the recent rise in homelessness is leading to a disproportionately large number of young homeless LGBT people who face serious barriers both in services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and in their ability to reconnect with their families and/ or enter employment or education. Simultaneously, there has been a reduction in LGBT-specific services that might help to address those issues. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Both these factors are resulting in a vastly increase</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d demand for services like AKT. Young LGBT people face a variety of complex issues and barriers folded in to their experience of family rejection and homelessness; i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is AKT's </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">contention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should not be forced by lack of services or support to retu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rn to homes where they face violence and abuse, including the emotional abuse caused by homophobia, biphobia and transphobia.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">10 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>